In either case, we need to prove `œá ‚Üí œÜ ‚àà T ‚à® ‚àÄ (Œì : Finset _), ...`.

Let's think. The induction hypothesis `ih` gives us that if `œÜ ‚àà construction T hT i`, then the property holds. So if we can show `œÜ ‚àà construction T hT i` from `œÜ ‚àà construction T hT (i + 1)`, we can apply `ih`.

In the case where `œÜ ‚àà construction T hT i` (from `decode i` is none), we can apply `ih`. The conclusion will be `œá ‚Üí œÜ ‚àà T ‚à® ‚àÄ (Œì : Finset _), ...`. This is exactly what we need to prove.

In the case where `œÜ = Œ¥` and `Œ¥ ‚àà construction T hT i` and the condition holds, we can also apply `ih` to `Œ¥ ‚àà construction T hT i`. The conclusion will be `œá ‚Üí Œ¥ ‚àà T ‚à® ‚àÄ (Œì : Finset _), ...`. Since `œÜ = Œ¥`, this becomes `œá ‚Üí œÜ ‚àà T ‚à® ‚àÄ (Œì : Finset _), ...`. This is also what we need to prove.

So the proof strategy is:
